John Edward: Language skills essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional exam results, which is underpinned by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community endeavours.
With over 30,000 pupils in Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide services at the highest level to pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for high school and higher education, their chosen career and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a special school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject of choice within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, your words will come to his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words reach his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year’s competition, we note that foreign languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest rates of promotion within independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied languages have obtained a Higher Grade A certificate.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students earned a Higher Grade A certificate in Mandarin; also 72% of those who study German, 69% of those who study French, and 63% of those who study Spanish earned such a certificate.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need in the future.
Now, foreign languages, as a subject, are held the same as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in independent school curricula and in other fields.
A survey by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that for the reasons employers gave for fighting for vacancies, 17% were attributed to a shortage of language skills.
As a result, language skills are increasingly becoming imperative for preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities requiring foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, having such a life-long skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to carry a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%.
That’s why investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
With more languages, especially in developing economies, children will be more likely to find meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, every school will teach other languages.
A number of schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will learn languages that are considered to be most important to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be more languages of choice within independent schools, with teachers who are specialized in this area.
Scottish Independent Schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and encourage them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may be.
It cannot be denied at this time, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be vital to the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should indeed be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right (we have to do it right).
