Harvard students take courses on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year encourages students to sleep more, in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture that makes them undergo “all-night” learning sessions, energized with lots of caffeine.
A scientist has discovered that students at the world’s most prestigious university often don’t even master the basic concepts of how they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, created the course, believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after holding a conference on the impact of lack of sleep on the ability to learn.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now, in the last year?’
She told me she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, introduced for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were seriously sleep-deprived during the week.
The one-hour course can involve a number of interactive tasks.
Within a section, the image of a dorm room is presented, and students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports pants and books to be told what the effects of caffeine and light are and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
“We know we can’t instantly change student behavior.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as everyone has the right to know about the health effects of smoking,” Professor Czeisler added.
The culture that makes students proud to have learned all night still exists, he says, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Sufficient, good-quality sleep should be a student’s “secret weapon” for combating stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even for avoiding weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain think the body is hungry, which makes students feel like they’re constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his courses in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to require all graduate students to complete a similar degree program before enrolling at this fiercely competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advised students to set an alarm to know when it’s time to go to sleep, as well as when to wake up, and to know the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and cause difficulties when trying to fall asleep.
