According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Canal de Saint-Quentin "through a very heavy fog and under the intense fire of artillery and machine guns".
Later, he hastened to the front line and, with "fantastic bravery", opened the way for the soldiers, then attacked a nest of artillery himself and managed to eliminate three of the detachment's weapons.
Lieutenant-Colonel Vann was killed by a German sniper on 4 October 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I can never match, but it makes me feel humbled.”
