He said: “So far, these feelings of inferiority, and the fact that I felt different, were the real things that gave me the strength and stamina to achieve success.”
He wanted to prove he was “someone,” he said, so as not to disappoint everyone when they finally learned about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medal winner became a prominent supporter of LGBT campaigns and took advantage of his appearance at this year’s Commonwealth Games in Australia to urge more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he decided to speak out because he felt lucky to be able to live freely, without consequences, and because he wanted to give others “hope.”
