National Trust Spies on the Secret Lives of Bats
New research being conducted on a Scottish Highlands property aims to reveal how bats use the environment to hunt their prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help future conservation activities.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will look at common dwarf bats and pygmy bats, as well as eared bats and water bats from Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations around the property to track bat activity throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by bats and what species emit certain sounds.
A habitat map and report will also be produced to create a detailed, scaled-up picture of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating lawns, and what is the best way to maintain forest meadows for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably over the past century.
They are endangered by construction and development work affecting their nests, but also by habitat loss.
Wind turbines and public lighting are also risks, as are fly traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, as well as attacks from domestic cats.
Actually, bats are not blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about bats.
They have ten trained experts, who periodically carry out surveys, control nests and sometimes carry out rescue missions.
The organisation has even created Scotland's first and only bat reserve, on the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, where eight of Scotland's ten bat species are found.
Estate manager David Thompson says this is ideal territory for bats.
“Here at Threave, the area is great for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand why they need to breed.”
It stresses the importance of looking for bats before performing maintenance work on properties, because simply unintentionally destroying a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and offspring, which can destroy the entire local population.
Bats are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and we don’t know how populations evolve for many of our species.”
