How can the US-China trade war benefit Beijing?
The salvos that heralded the start of the trade war between the United States and China have been deafening, and while it appears to be a long way to go, the feuds between the two countries could be beneficial for Beijing in the long run, experts say.
Donald Trump, the president of the United States, issued the first warning earlier this year, imposing tariffs on key imports from China, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation came this week with new tariffs affecting $200bn (<0xC2><0xA3>150bn) worth of goods, effectively taxing half of all goods from China entering the United States.
Beijing has retaliated each time, most recently imposing a tax of between 5 and 10 percent on $60 billion worth of U.S. goods.
China has warned that it will respond to every blow from the United States, and it is unlikely that the world’s second-largest economy will take a step back in the near future.
For Washington to withdraw, China must agree to its demands, but publicly ceding to the United States would be far too humiliating for Xi Jinping, China’s president.
However, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards right, U.S. pressure on the trade war could support China positively in the long run, reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a quick policy decision taken in Washington or Beijing could lead to an economic collapse in both countries would in fact be more dangerous than what has been expected so far,” said Abigail Grace, an associate researcher focusing on Asia at the Center for New American Security, an expert group.
Syria is ready for the return of refugees, says Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is seeking help to rebuild the country ravaged by a war that has lasted for more than seven years.
During his speech at the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the situation in the country was improving.
“Today, the conditions on the ground are more stable and secure, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate the areas destroyed by the terrorists so that things return to normal.
The existing conditions allow for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they have been forced to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures targeting their daily lives and livelihoods.
The United Nations estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country since war broke out in 2011.
Six million people who continue to live in the country are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem said the Syrian regime would welcome help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he stressed that conditional assistance or aid from countries sponsored by the insurgency would not be accepted.
