Red Tide News: Concentrations Drop in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Wildlife Protection Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations for certain areas of the Tampa Bay.
According to the Commission, uneven inflorescence conditions are reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – suggesting lower concentrations.
This red tide inflorescence extends over a coastline of about 210 km from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The spots can be found about 10 miles (16 km) off Hillsborough County, but in fewer places than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Average concentrations found in or near Pinellas County were reported last week, as well as low to high concentrations in Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations in Sarasota County, and high to low concentrations in Lee County, and background to medium concentrations in Charlotte County.
Respiratory tract irritation continues to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier counties.
There have been no reported cases of airway irritation in northwestern Florida in the past week.
